      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "0782bb7602d7f5d4da87c80fb917a8b025f206ed",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 148,
        "name": "Chris Horn",
        "email": "chris.horn@hpe.com",
        "username": "hornc"
      },
      "date": "2021-11-17 19:32:08.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> > If cmid->device == NULL is being treated as an error then why are\n > > we returning > 0 in this case?\n > \n > Because any rc != 0 means error\n\nHmm, then this code in kiblnd_failover_thread() is confusing, but I'm admittedly not super familiar with this code:\n\n                        rc = kiblnd_dev_failover(dev, ns);\n\n                        write_lock_irqsave(glock, flags);\n\n                        LASSERT(dev->ibd_failover);\n                        dev->ibd_failover = 0;\n                        if (rc >= 0) { /* Device is OK or failover succeed */\n                                dev->ibd_next_failover = ktime_get_seconds() + 3;\n                                continue;\n                        }\n\n                        /* failed to failover, retry later */\n                        dev->ibd_next_failover = ktime_get_seconds() +\n                                min(dev->ibd_failed_failover, 10);",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "96cc1c7e41848b677590c2453ca4ae3023569490",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 824,
        "name": "Serguei Smirnov",
        "email": "ssmirnov@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "ssmirnov"
      },
      "date": "2021-11-18 17:40:25.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> > > If cmid->device == NULL is being treated as an error then why\n > are\n > > > we returning > 0 in this case?\n > >\n > > Because any rc != 0 means error\n > \n > Hmm, then this code in kiblnd_failover_thread() is confusing, but\n > I'm admittedly not super familiar with this code:\n > \n > rc = kiblnd_dev_failover(dev, ns);\n > \n > write_lock_irqsave(glock, flags);\n > \n > LASSERT(dev->ibd_failover);\n > dev->ibd_failover = 0;\n > if (rc >= 0) { /* Device is OK or failover succeed */\n > dev->ibd_next_failover = ktime_get_seconds() + 3;\n > continue;\n > }\n > \n > /* failed to failover, retry later */\n > dev->ibd_next_failover = ktime_get_seconds() +\n > min(dev->ibd_failed_failover, 10);\n\nTrue, positive return code is for \"we didn't really failover, but the device is ok, so we won't retry\" case. So for this patch the idea is that we detect a situation when we don't want to failover if cmid->device is NULL. The question is, even though we could bind, is it a \"device ok\" situation and would retrying help.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "961dfece4865370e978058138b9e423f0f32e48a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 148,
        "name": "Chris Horn",
        "email": "chris.horn@hpe.com",
        "username": "hornc"
      },
      "date": "2021-11-18 20:03:41.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nbq. The question is, even though we could bind, is it a \"device ok\" situation and would retrying help.\n\nCan you answer that question? As I said, I'm not very familiar with this particular code, so it isn't obvious to me that this change in behavior is correct or doesn't have other side effects. If we're hitting a NULL deref in kiblnd_set_ni_fatal_on() (or when calling that function) then there are obviously other ways to handle that, so i'd like to understand why this particular solution is the best one.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "be490ab3ea998601f350cd684cb8212161c3864f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 824,
        "name": "Serguei Smirnov",
        "email": "ssmirnov@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "ssmirnov"
      },
      "date": "2021-11-24 23:37:36.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nI'm not entirely sure. The idea was that this is a kind of odd transient situation that's unlikely to repeat if we retry. But because there's no confidence that the change in return code behaviour is useful, I can just update this patch such that the old behaviour (pre-\"4668283cd1\") is maintained but we still make sure not to call \"set_ni_fatal\" if rc is 0 and device is NULL.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
